/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerfect Worlds is an extensive, comparative study of utopian narratives in both the East and the West. Douwe Fokkema provides an elegant argument about the human impulse to imagine new and better worlds, astutely observing that the utopian imagination thrives in the context of secularization. Fokkema also tracks the rise of dystopian narratives, invoking authors as diverse as Margaret Atwood and Lao She, and provides a cogent evaluation of the role of imagined worlds in both Chinese and Euro-American fiction. A shrewd comparison of cultures, as well as a vivid account of cross-cultural influence, this volume is a welcome addition to the scholarly discourse on utopias.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChinese fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aComparative literaturexWestern and Chinese. 0aUtopias in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aUtopias in literature. 0aUtopias. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aThomassen, Jacques, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 avan Ommen, Kasper, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048514861zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048514861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048514861.jpg  a978-3-11-070067-1  AUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK